SIMPLE: swash
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swash
<hw>Swash</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Swash</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>, <er>Squash</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An oval figure, whose moldings are oblique to
the axis of the work.</def> <rj><au>Moxon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Swash plate</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a revolving
circular plate, set obliquely on its shaft, and acting as a cam to give
a reciprocating motion to a rod in a direction parallel to the
shaft.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swash</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swash
<hw>Swash</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Swash</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>, <er>Squash</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>Soft, like fruit
too ripe; swashy.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Pegge.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swash</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swash
<hw>Swash</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Swashed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swashing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably of imitative origin;
cf. Sw. <ets>svasska</ets> to splash, and, for sense 3, Sw.
<ets>svassa</ets> to bully, to rodomontade.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
dash or flow noisily, as water; to splash; <as>as, water
<ex>swashing</ex> on a shallow place</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fall violently or noisily.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Holinshed.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bluster; to make a great noise; to vapor or
brag.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swash</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Swash
<hw>Swash</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Impulse of water flowing
with violence; a dashing or splashing of water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A narrow sound or channel of water lying within a
sand bank, or between a sand bank and the shore, or a bar over which the
sea washes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Liquid filth; wash; hog mash.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A blustering noise; a swaggering behavior.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A swaggering fellow; a swasher.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swashbuckler</ent>⟦br⟧
